result.execSummary:
The defendant Garrett L. Nundahl was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture or Deliver Prescription Drug, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 450.11(9)(b).
  • Manufacture/Deliver Schedule IV Drugs, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(i).
  • Manufacture/Deliver Schedule IV Drugs, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(i).

Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. records.addlTxt:
Defendant Garrett L. Nundahl in court with attorney Peter A. Bartelt. Prosecuting Atty Jennifer M. Harper appeared for State of Wisconsin.  DA Harper details the parties' joint agreement:  Count 1:  27 mo initial confinement and 18 mo extended supervision, consecutive, imposed/stayed for 5 years probation consecutive to any other with conditions to be determined by the agent.  Count 2:  18 mo initial confinement and 18 mo extended supervision, consecutive to any other sentence and Count 1, also imposed/stayed for probation of five years.  Count 3:  18 mo initial confinement and 18 mo extended supervision, concurrent with Count 2 if revoked, also imposed/stayed for 5 years probation.  Def pleads guilty to counts 1, 2, and 3.  Court's colloquy re pleas.  Finding of guilty.

Sentence:

Count 1 - 27 mo initial confinement and 18 mo ES (45 mo WI State Prison sentence), consecutive to any other sentence def is serving.  THat is imposed/stayed for 5 years probation, consecutive to any sentence def is serving.  Conditions to be determined by probation agent.  Pay costs.

Count 2 - 36 mo total sentence with 18 mo initial and 18 mo ES, also consecutive to any other sentences.  Imposed/stayed for 5 years probation with same conditions he comply with all rules/requirements of the agent.  Costs.

Count 3 - 36 mo total with 18 mo initial and 18 mo ES, concurrent with Count 2.  Imposed and stayed for 5 years conditions with same conditions.  Costs.

Def presently at Stanley Correctional.

Court provides felony conviction admonishment re lifetime firearm prohibition as well as civil rights suspension during the time def is on the sentence.

Def has already provided the DNA sample.  Court still, however, imposes the DNA surcharge, per count, as such is mandatory.
